sys.argv



sys.argv returns a list containing the program's filename [0] and arguments from the command line [1:] (not from IDLE!). If command line arguments have been provided, then len(sys.argv) evaluates to an integer greater than 1.

In order to execute, start script (eg "map.py") from the command line in the current working directory, e.g. "map first_arg second_arg"

EXAMPLE
#opens google maps with address from command line:
import webbrowser, sys

address = '+'.join(sys.argv[1:])
webbrowser.open('https://www.google.com/maps/place/' + address)